":"Ponce Lusignan于1034年出生在法国皮卡迪索姆馬賀-拉盧瓦德。她于大约1057年与Audebert II de la Marche在法国諾門迪结婚。他们至少是2个儿子和4个女儿的父母。她去世于1076年在法国享年42岁。"},"hr":{"1034–1076":"1034.–1076.","1020–1088":"1020–1088","1055–Female":"1055–preminula","1062–1116":"1062.–1116","–1080":"–1080","–1091":"–1091","–1092":"–1092","–1140":"–1140","1091":"1091","1080":"1080","1055":"1055","1088":"1088","1076":"1076.","1020":"1020","1140":"1140","1062":"1062.","1092":"1092","1116":"1116","1034":"1034.","about 1057":"oko 1057.","about 1055":"oko 1055.","Duchy of Normandy":"Normandie, Francuska","Charroux, Vienne, France":"Charroux, Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Francuska","France":"Francuska","La Marche, Gironde, Aquitaine, France":"La Marche, Gironde, Aquitaine, Francuska","Marché-Allouarde, Somme, Picardie, France":"Marché-Allouarde, Somme, Picardie, Francuska"},"cs":{"1034–1076":"1034–1076","1020–1088":"1020–1088","1055–Female":"1055–Zesnulá","1062–1116":"1062–1116","–1080":"–1080","–1091":"–1091","–1092":"–1092","–1140":"–1140","1091":"1091","1080":"1080","1055":"1055","1088":"1088","1076":"1076","1020":"1020","1140":"1140","1062":"1062","1092":"1092","1116":"1116","1034":"1034","about 1057":"okolo 1057","about 1055":"okolo 1055","Duchy of Normandy":"Normandie, Francie","Charroux, Vienne, France":"Charroux, Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Francie","France":"Francie","La Marche, Gironde, Aquitaine, France":"La Marche, Gironde, Aquitaine, Francie","Marché-Allouarde, Somme, Picardie, France":"Marché-Allouarde, Somme, Picardie, Francie"},"da":{"1034–1076":"1034–1076","1020–1088":"1020–1088","1055–Female":"1055–Afdød","1062–1116":"1062–1116","–1080":"–1080","–1091":"–1091","–1092":"–1092","–1140":"–1140","1091":"1091","1080":"1080","1055":"1055","1088":"1088","1076":"1076","1020":"1020","1140":"1140","1062":"1062","1092":"1092","1116":"1116","1034":"1034","about 1057":"omkring 1057","about 1055":"omkring 1055","Duchy of Normandy":"Normandie, Frankrig","Charroux, Vienne, France":"Charroux, Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Frankrig","France":"Frankrig","La Marche, Gironde, Aquitaine, France":"La Marche, Gironde, Aquitaine, Frankrig","Marché-Allouarde, Somme, Picardie, France":"Marché-Allouarde, Somme, Picardie, Frankrig"},"nl":{"1034–1076":"1034–1076","1020–1088":"1020–1088","1055–Female":"1055–Overleden","1062–1116":"1062–1116","–1080":"–1080","–1091":"–1091","–1092":"–1092","–1140":"–1140","1091":"1091","1080":"1080","1055":"1055","1088":"1088","1076":"1076","1020":"1020","1140":"1140","1062":"1062","1092":"1092","1116":"1116","1034":"1034","about 1057":"circa 1057","about 1055":"circa 1055","Duchy of Normandy":"Normandie, Frankrijk","Charroux, Vienne, France":"Charroux, Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Frankrijk","France":"Frankrijk","La Marche, Gironde, Aquitaine, France":"La Marche, Gironde, Aquitaine, Frankrijk","Marché-Allouarde, Somme, Picardie, France":"Marché-Allouarde, Somme, Picardie, Frankrijk"},"en":{"1034–1076":"1034–1076","1020–1088":"1020–1088","1055–Female":"1055–Deceased","1062–1116":"1062–1116","–1080":"–1080","–1091":"–1091","–1092":"–1092","–1140":"–1140","1091":"1091","1080":"1080","1055":"1055","1088":"1088","1076":"1076","1020":"1020","1140":"1140","1062":"1062","1092":"1092","1116":"1116","1034":"1034","about 1057":"about 1057","about 1055":"about 1055","Duchy of Normandy":"Normandy, France","Charroux, Vienne, France":"Charroux, Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France","France":"France","La Marche, Gironde, Aquitaine, France":"La Marche, Gironde, Aquitaine, France","Marché-Allouarde, Somme, Picardie, France":"Marché-Allouarde, Somme, Picardie, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lusignan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Normand, Andre, Francois, Lucien, Marcel.","French: habitational name from Lusignan, a place in Vienne. This surname is very rare in France. Compare   Zeno  .","History: Jean Miel (or Amiel) <i>dit</i> Lusignan from Lusignan in Vienne, France, married Marie-Thérèse Latouche in Boucherville, QC, in 1699. — A French family called <i>(de) Lusignan</i> became enormously powerful in the eastern Mediterranean during the Middle Ages. Guy de Lusignan (1129–94) was king of Cyprus from 1192 to 1194 (and before that, by right of marriage, king of the crusader state of Jerusalem). Hugues de Lusignan was king of Cyprus from 1267 to 1284 and king of Jerusalem from 1268 to 1284. During the 14th century, Lusignans became kings of the Armenian kingdom of Cilicia (on the Mediterranean coast of what is now Turkey, facing Cyprus)."],"variants":[{"name":"Zeno","meanings":["Italian (mainly southern Italy), Hispanic (mainly Puerto Rico), and African American: from the personal name <i>Zeno</i>, classical Greek <i>Zēnōn</i>, a derivative of <i>Zeus</i>, the name of the king of the gods in Greek mythology. <i>Zeno</i> or <i>Zenone</i> is the name of a 4th-century Italian saint from Verona. As an African American name it was probably adopted in honor of the Stoic philosopher Zeno of Kition.","Altered form of French   Lusignan  ."]}]},{"name":"Ponce","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Juan, Luis, Jesus, Carlos, Francisco, Jorge, Miguel, Pedro, Raul, Roberto.","Spanish and French: from the medieval personal name <i>Ponce</i>, ultimately from <i>Pontius</i>, a Roman surname, perhaps an ethnic name for someone from <i>Pontus</i> (named from Greek <i>pontos</i> ‘ocean’) in Asia Minor, or an Italic cognate of Latin <i>Quintus</i> ‘fifth’ (i.e. ‘fifth-born’). The name was borne by two 3rd-century Christian saints, a Carthaginian deacon and a martyr of Nice, but was not widely popular in the Middle Ages because of the inhibiting influence of the even more famous Pontius Pilate. In some cases though, the surname may have been originally used for someone who had played the part of this character in a religious play."],"variants":[{"name":"Ponce de Leon","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Luis, Cesar, Mercedes, Alberto, Francisco, Javier, Juan, Lazaro, Leticia, Manuel, Ramon.","Spanish (<b>Ponce de León</b>): compound of the surname   Ponce   + the habitational name <i>León</i> (see   Leon  ).","History: Juan Ponce De León, the Spanish explorer who discovered Florida, came from a noble Aragonese family. He is believed to have been on board for Columbus's second voyage to Hispaniola in 1493. After his death in Florida from a wound from an Indian arrow in 1521, Ponce De León's title and rights in Florida were passed on to his son."]},{"name":"Points","meanings":["English (of Norman origin):","from the Old French personal name <i>Ponz</i>, <i>Ponce</i>, from Latin <i>Pontius</i> (see   Ponce  ).","habitational name from any of several places called Ponts (such as those in Manche and in Seine-Maritime, Normandy), from Latin <i>pontes</i> ‘bridges’. This name has been established since the 13th century in Ireland, where it appears as <i>Pounce</i> and <i>Pounche</i>, and is Gaelicized as <b>Púinse</b>."]},{"name":"Pons","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Pedro, Ramon, Guillermo, Roberto, Carlos, Francisco, Luis, Mario, Rafael, Apolonia.  French Adrien, Armand, Emile, Jacques, Marcel, Marcelle, Matilde.","Catalan, French (Occitan), and Dutch: from the medieval personal name <i>Pons</i> (see   Ponce  ).","German: patronymic from a short form of an ancient Germanic personal name, such as <i>Bonhard</i>, formed with the element <i>bon</i> ‘request, petition’ (compare Latin <i>bonus</i>)."]},{"name":"Ponzio","meanings":["From Latin <i>Pontius</i>, a family name of uncertain origin."]},{"name":"Poncelet","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alain, Benoit.  German Erwin, Fritz.","French (mainly northeastern) and Walloon:","topographic name from a diminutive of Old French <i>poncel</i> ‘little bridge’, or a habitational name from (Le) Poncelet, the name of several places in the northeastern part of France."]},{"name":"Poinsett","meanings":["Altered form of French <b>Poinset</b>: from a pet form of the personal name <i>Poinse</i>, from Latin <i>Pontius</i> (see   Ponce  ). Altered ending reflects the Canadian and American French practice of sounding the final <i>-t</i>. The surname <i>Poinset</i> is very rare in France.","History: The <i>poinsettia</i> takes its name from an American diplomat, Joel Poinsett (1779–1851), who was a keen amateur botanist and who brought the flower back from Mexico, where he was US ambassador. He was born in Charleston, SC, and was descended from a Huguenot, Pierre Poinset, who was born in Soubise in Charente-Maritime and settled in Charleston <i>c.</i> 1700. Pierre Poinset is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar registers of the Huguenot Society of America and of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."]},{"name":"Point","meanings":["French: from the personal name <i>Point</i>, from Latin <i>Pontius</i> (see   Ponce  ).","English: variant of   Points   with loss of final <i>-s</i>. This surname is rare in Britain."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Ponce Lusignan was born in 1034, in Marché-Allouarde, Somme, Picardie, France. She married Audebert II de la Marche about 1057, in Normandy, France. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 4 daughters. She died in 1076, in France, at the age of 42."},"et":{"1034–1076":"1034–1076","1020–1088":"1020–1088","1055–Female":"1055–Surnud","1062–1116":"1062–1116","–1080":"–1080","–1091":"–1091","–1092":"–1092","–1140":"–1140","1091":"1091","1080":"1080","1055":"1055","1088":"1088","1076":"1076","1020":"1020","1140":"1140","1062":"1062","1092":"1092","1116":"1116","1034":"1034","about 1057":"umbes 1057","about 1055":"umbes 1055","Duchy of Normandy":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Charroux, Vienne, France":"Charroux, Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Prantsusmaa","France":"Pra